between Byron's fragmentary or "workless" poetic and romantic poetry generally, and to articulate connections between romantic poetry and modern literature and literary theory. The book also argues that the "exigency" or "imperative" of the fragmentary works of Schlegel, Byron, Joyce, and Blanchot is not so much the expression of a style as it is an acknowledgment of what remains unthought in thinking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEuropean poetryy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEuropean poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRomanticismzEurope. 4aGeneral Interest : Poetry. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aLiterature : Romanticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791483244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791483244/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles